Fill the NA’s in Age

library(randomForest)
library(dplyr)

separate the train & test data

with_age <- subset(raw_data, Age != "NA")
set.seed(66)
train_age <- sample_frac(with_age, size = 0.7 )   # use sample_frac() to sellect 70% of the data randomly
test_age <- setdiff(with_age, train_age)      # use sediff() to sellect the observations not being selected by train_age

construct model

forest_fit_age <- randomForest(Age ~ Survived + Pclass + Sex + SibSp + Parch + Fare , data = train_age, ntree = 100)

use the modle to predict test

prediction <- predict(forest_fit_age, newdata = test_age[, c( "Survived","Pclass", "Sex", "SibSp", "Parch", "Fare" )], type = "class")
#prediction <- predict(forest_fit_age, newdata = test_age[, c( "Survived","Pclass", "Sex", "SibSp", "Parch", "Fare" )], type = "response")
# these two types end up same result

calculate prediction error (root mean square error)

rmse_age <- (prediction - test_age$Age)^2 %>%
  mean() %>%
  sqrt() %>%
  round(2)
rmse_age
## [1] 12.08
# it's accepatable

replace the NA’s with prediction in age

without_age <- setdiff(raw_data, with_age)
Age <- predict(forest_fit_age, newdata = without_age[ , c( "Survived","Pclass", "Sex", "SibSp", "Parch", "Fare" )], type = "class")
tmp <- without_age
tmp$Age <- NULL
full_data <- cbind(tmp, Age) %>%
  merge(with_age,all.x = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)

Fill the null in Embarked with S

full_data$Embarked <- as.character(full_data$Embarked)
full_data$Embarked[full_data$Embarked == ""] <- "S"
full_data$Embarked <- factor(full_data$Embarked)

Exporatory statistical analysis: principal components analysis

data_for_pca <- select(full_data, Pclass, Sex, SibSp, Parch, Fare,  Age)
data_for_pca$Sex <- as.numeric(data_for_pca$Sex)
titanic.pca <- prcomp(data_for_pca, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)

Build survival model

library(randomForest)
set.seed(666)
train_sur <- sample_frac(full_data, size = 0.7)
test_sur <- setdiff(full_data, train_sur)
train_sur$Survived <- as.factor(train_sur$Survived)   # needed for classification
forest_fit_sur <- randomForest( Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, data = train_sur, ntree = 100 )

# use the modle to predict test

prediction_sur <- predict(forest_fit_sur, test_sur[, c("Pclass", "Sex", "Age", "SibSp", "Parch", "Fare", "Embarked")], type = "class")

calculate accuracy

confusion_matrix <- table(test_sur$Survived, prediction_sur)
accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion_matrix)) / sum(confusion_matrix)
accuracy
## [1] 0.8576779

find 86 NA’s in Age and 1 NA’s in Fare

to_predict <- read.csv("~/Dropbox/Course/Y2/R langeuage/final_work/test.csv")

fill Age NA’s

fit_age_no_sur <- randomForest(Age ~ Pclass + Sex + SibSp + Parch + Fare , data = train_age, ntree = 100)

tmp <- to_predict[is.na(to_predict$Age), ]
t_with_age <- tmp[ ,c("Pclass", "Sex", "Age", "SibSp", "Parch", "Fare", "Embarked")] %>%
  predict(fit_age_no_sur, . , type = "class" )

tmp$Age <- t_with_age
filter_to_predict <- subset(to_predict, Age != "NA")
to_predict <- merge(filter_to_predict, tmp, all.x = TRUE,  all.y = TRUE)

fill Fare NA’s data

fare_mean <- mean(to_predict$Fare, na.rm = TRUE)
to_predict$Fare[is.na(to_predict$Fare)] <- fare_mean
